With effect from midnight on Tuesday 24 March (local time) the Turks and Caicos Islandsâ€™ borders will be closed until midnight on Tuesday 14 April (local time). During this time, non-residents of the Turks and Caicos Islands will not be allowed entry into the territory.
Turks and Caicos residents who are currently outside of the territory will still be permitted to return to the Turks and Caicos Islands during this time, but will be subject to requisite health stipulations based on risk assessment. Returning non-symptomatic residents will be required to self-quarantine for a period as advised at the time of return. Residents arriving in the Islands after travel to, from or through an infected country will be subjected to screening and passenger tracing at port of entry, subjected to clinical examination at port of entry, and quarantined for a period of fourteen days as deemed necessary. Further information on risks to travellers, avoidance measures, symptoms and how to self-quarantine is available at TCI Ministry of Health.
Non-residents and visitors currently in the Turks and Caicos Islands will be allowed to leave the Turks and Caicos Islands during this period, but will not be allowed to re-enter while borders remain closed.
We strongly encourage any non-resident British visitors on holiday to the Turks and Caicos Islands to consider leaving as soon as possible to avoid difficulties they will face if travel out of the territory and the wider region are further restricted and they are unable to get home.
All regional and international commercial passenger and private flights, along with international seafaring, will cease to operate into the Turks and Caicos Islands. Cargo and courier flights, and emergency flights e.g. medical evacuations, will continue. Cargo vessels will continue to operate into the Turks and Caicos Islands. More information is available on the TCI Government website.
All schools, nurseries, Community College and UWI Open Campus will be closed from the end of the day on Friday 20 March 2020 until 20 April 2020.
A ban is in place on all gatherings in public places of over 25 people, including schools, places of Worship, places of entertainment or refreshment, funerals, sporting events and other social gatherings. Movement of people between islands is discouraged.
We strongly encourage any non-resident British visitors on holiday to the Turks and Caicos Island to consider leaving as soon as possible to avoid difficulties they will face if travel out of the territory and the wider region are further restricted and they are unable to get home. See Return to the UK.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
